---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";

const title = "SplatForge — on-prem codec (enterprise)";
const description =
  "Self-hosted Docker image for the SplatForge codec. Same compression numbers as the hosted SaaS, deployable on your own NVIDIA GPU — for air-gap, defense, healthcare, and automotive customers who can't send training data to a third-party endpoint.";

// Bench expectations are identical to /docs/qat-bundle — same trainer,
// same recipe, same numbers. The on-prem image is a packaging
// difference, not an algorithmic one.
const benchExpectations = [
  { scene: "bonsai",   psnr: "+0.58 dB", save: "40.5%",  note: "best-case (indoor, dense cams)" },
  { scene: "garden",   psnr: "+0.19 dB", save: "40.5%",  note: "high-quality outdoor" },
  { scene: "bicycle",  psnr: "+0.09 dB", save: "40.5%",  note: "challenging outdoor" },
  { scene: "stump",    psnr: "+0.04 dB", save: "33.9%",  note: "outdoor with sky" },
  { scene: "treehill", psnr: "+0.07 dB", save: "33.7%",  note: "outdoor foliage" },
  { scene: "flowers",  psnr: "+0.03 dB", save: "33.8%",  note: "worst-case (close-up, low cam count)" },
];
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <nav class="nav" aria-label="Primary">
    <a href="/" class="nav-brand">
      <span class="dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      splatforge
    </a>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <a href="/#docs">Quickstart</a>
      <a href="/bench">SplatBench</a>
      <a href="/import">Import</a>
      <a href="/pricing">Pricing</a>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <h1>On-prem codec (enterprise)</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    A self-hosted Docker image of the SplatForge codec for customers
    whose training data can't leave their network. Defense, healthcare,
    automotive, and any other regulated environment runs the same
    binary that backs the hosted SaaS — same per-scene numbers, same
    API contract, your hardware.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Licensing:</strong> bundled with the
    <a href="/pricing#team">Team Seat</a> plan as an
    Ed25519-signed entitlement. Your license token is checked at
    container start; it cannot be exfiltrated to enable a second
    install. <strong>Image distribution:</strong> private registry,
    pull-credentials issued per customer.
  </p>

  <h2>System requirements</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>GPU:</strong> NVIDIA with ≥ 24 GB VRAM
      (A6000 / A100 / L40 / H100 / RTX 4090).</li>
    <li><strong>Driver:</strong> CUDA 12.1 or newer on the host.</li>
    <li><strong>Docker:</strong> 24.0 or newer with
      <code>nvidia-container-toolkit</code> installed so
      <code>--gpus all</code> works.</li>
    <li><strong>Disk:</strong> 16 GB for the image plus your training
      data. Image is ~7 GB compressed.</li>
    <li><strong>RAM:</strong> 32 GB host RAM recommended; the trainer
      streams scenes from disk so peak host-side memory stays small.</li>
    <li><strong>Network:</strong> none required at runtime. Air-gapped
      installs use <code>docker load</code> from an offline tarball;
      we ship a flat tarball alongside the registry image.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Quickstart</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Pull the image</strong> from the private registry
      (credentials issued with your contract):
      <pre><code>docker pull ghcr.io/splatforge/codec:latest</code></pre>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Start the container</strong> with your signed license
      token:
      <pre><code>docker run --gpus all -p 8080:8080 \
  -e SPLATFORGE_LICENSE=&quot;$TOKEN&quot; \
  ghcr.io/splatforge/codec:latest</code></pre>
      A missing or expired token exits the container with
      <code>exit 1</code> before CUDA initializes — no
      partial-startup state.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Verify the install:</strong>
      <pre><code>curl http://localhost:8080/healthz
# {`{`}"ok":true,"service":"splatforge-codec","gpu_available":true,
#  "license_customer":"Acme Defense","license_expiry":"2027-12-31"{`}`}</code></pre>
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>API contract</h2>
  <p>
    The on-prem image exposes the same routes as the hosted Modal
    endpoints, so existing customer code that targets
    <a href="/docs/api/qat-scaffold"><code>splatforge-qat-scaffold</code></a>
    or
    <a href="/docs/qat-bundle"><code>splatforge-qat-bundle</code></a>
    works unchanged — just point it at your container's URL instead of
    the hosted host.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>GET  /healthz</code> — liveness probe, returns license
      metadata and GPU status.</li>
    <li><code>GET  /license</code> — full license payload for
      diagnostics.</li>
    <li><code>POST /qat-scaffold</code> — single-PLY compression.
      Request body matches the hosted SaaS payload; for air-gap
      installs, pass <code>local_path</code> instead of
      <code>blob_url</code> after mounting the file with
      <code>-v</code>.</li>
    <li><code>POST /qat-bundle</code> — full-retrain compression with
      QAT finetune. Same payload shape as the hosted endpoint.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Compression numbers</h2>
  <p>
    Identical to the hosted SaaS. The on-prem image vendors the same
    QAT trainer; per-scene results are bit-comparable across the two
    deployment surfaces. Numbers from the public bench
    (<a href="/bench">/bench</a>, commit <code>c3387b3</code>):
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Scene</th><th>ΔPSNR</th><th>PLY save</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {benchExpectations.map((row) => (
        <tr>
          <td><code>{row.scene}</code></td>
          <td>{row.psnr}</td>
          <td>{row.save}</td>
          <td>{row.note}</td>
        </tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Validate the install (smoke test)</h2>
  <p>
    Each install ships with a tiny sample bundle and a smoke script.
    From the host that's running the container:
  </p>
  <pre><code>curl -O https://splatforge.com/sample/bonsai-tiny.tar.gz
curl -O https://splatforge.com/sample/smoke.sh
chmod +x smoke.sh
./smoke.sh bonsai-tiny.tar.gz http://localhost:8080</code></pre>
  <p>
    The script hits <code>/healthz</code>, <code>/license</code>, and
    <code>/qat-bundle</code> and prints the response shape. If any
    step fails, the script exits non-zero with a clear error.
  </p>

  <h2>Air-gapped install</h2>
  <p>
    For environments with no outbound internet, request the offline
    tarball from <a href="mailto:sales@splatforge.com">sales@splatforge.com</a>
    after your contract is signed. Load it once on the target host:
  </p>
  <pre><code>docker load -i splatforge-codec-0.1.0.tar.gz
docker run --gpus all -p 8080:8080 \
  -e SPLATFORGE_LICENSE=&quot;$TOKEN&quot; \
  splatforge/codec:0.1.0</code></pre>

  <h2>License rotation</h2>
  <p>
    Tokens are Ed25519-signed JSON payloads. They carry a customer
    label, an issue date, an expiry date, and a feature list. Expired
    tokens are rejected before CUDA loads — there is no grace period,
    by design. Renewal tokens are issued a month before expiry; rotate
    by restarting the container with the new
    <code>SPLATFORGE_LICENSE</code> env var.
  </p>

  <h2>Pricing</h2>
  <p>
    Included in the
    <a href="/pricing#team">Team Seat</a> plan. Per-image runtime is
    unmetered — you pay for the seat, not for compute. See
    <a href="/pricing">/pricing</a> for tier details, or
    <a href="mailto:sales@splatforge.com">email sales</a> for a defense
    or government quote.
  </p>

  <p>
